SIMPLE: misprision
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Misprision
<hw>Mis*pri"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>misprisio</ets>, or OF. <ets>mesprison</ets>, prop., a mistaking,
but confused with OF. <ets>mespris</ets> contempt, F.
<ets>m⟦eacute⟧pris</ets>. See 2d <er>Misprise</er>, <er>Misprize</er>,
<er>Prison</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of misprising; misapprehension;
misconception; mistake.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>
<rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>misprision</qex> of this passage has aided in fostering
the delusive notion.</q> <rj><qau>Hare.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Neglect; undervaluing; contempt.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A neglect, negligence, or
contempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In its larger and older sense it was used to signify
⟦ldquo⟧every considerable misdemeanor which has not a certain name given
to it in the law.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Russell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
In a more modern sense it is applied exclusively to two offenses: --⟦br⟧
<b>1.</b> <col><b>Misprision of treason</b></col>, which is omission to
notify the authorities of an act of treason by a person cognizant
thereof. <au>Stephen.</au>⟦br⟧
<b>2.</b> <col><b>Misprision of felony</b></col>, which is a concealment
of a felony by a person cognizant thereof.
<rj><au>Stephen.</au></rj></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 931 --></p>

<p><ent>Misprize</ent>⟦br⟧
